				\begin{document}$$\mathbf m _{j} = \text {dim}(\{m_{j}\})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M98"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">m</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mtext>dim</mml:mtext><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">{</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq46.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Any collective noise operator that does not distinguish spins acts trivially on the symmetry label. More precisely, all components of the total spin angular momentum, <inline-formula id="IEq47"><alternatives><tex-math id="M99">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
