</p><p id="Par14">Realistically, a methyl group in a symmetric top molecules like <inline-formula id="IEq76"><alternatives><tex-math id="M167">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X-CH_{3}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M168"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>C</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>H</mml:mi><mml:mn>3</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq76.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> does not rotate freely due to the existence of a <italic>hindering</italic> potential which is imposed by the rest of the molecule as well as other external molecules<xref ref-type="fn" rid="Fn1">1</xref>. In ethane, for example, the molecule prefers to be in the staggered configuration rather than the eclipsed configuration [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR21">21</xref>]. The amount of energy that is required to move from one configuration to another defines the height of the hindering potential or the <italic>barrier</italic> (Fig.&#x000a0;<xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>). Therefore, in addition to the free rotation term, there is an extra potential that affects the rotational motion [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR14">14</xref>],<disp-formula id="Equ9"><label>9</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M169">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
