				\begin{document}$$\epsilon = e^{i\frac{2 \pi }{3}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M348"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003f5;</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c0;</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mn>3</mml:mn></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow></mml:msup></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq159.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Because of the cyclic boundary condition, we have <inline-formula id="IEq160"><alternatives><tex-math id="M349">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi ^{j}(\varphi + \frac{2\pi }{3})= \chi ^{j+1}(\varphi )$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M350"><mml:mrow><mml:msup><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c7;</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c6;</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c0;</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mn>3</mml:mn></mml:mfrac><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c7;</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c6;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq160.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Consequently, the <inline-formula id="IEq161"><alternatives><tex-math id="M351">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\lambda =0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M352"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003bb;</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq161.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> state has <italic>A</italic> symmetry and the <inline-formula id="IEq162"><alternatives><tex-math id="M353">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\lambda =\pm 1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M354"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003bb;</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo>&#x000b1;</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq162.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> states have <inline-formula id="IEq163"><alternatives><tex-math id="M355">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_{\pm }$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M356"><mml:msub><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x000b1;</mml:mo></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq163.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> symmetry. We should also note that the above LCAO expansions are valid in the limit of no-hybridization assumption where the overlap between <inline-formula id="IEq164"><alternatives><tex-math id="M357">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi ^{(j)}_{n}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M358"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">&#x003c7;</mml:mi><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>j</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11128_2017_1792_Article_IEq164.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq165"><alternatives><tex-math id="M359">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
